page.title: 15LARKEY VALLEY THANINGTON 2
page.content: In the wood, now declared of Special Scientific Interest, dominant species of trees are beech, sweet chestnut, oak, birch and ash. Hornbeam can also be found. Most trees are native speci- mens except the sweet chestnut, probably brought here by the Romans. Shrubs such as the wayfaring tree, dogwood and wild privet occur natur- ally on the chalk soil. Plants include sanicle, moschatel, sweet woobine, angelica and orchids. Spring brings primroses, wood anemones and violets and summer an abundance of nettle leaved bell flower. Many species of birds and butterflies can be seen also squirrels and dormice. Paths have been laid out and marked as nature trails and walks. 3 Bridleways cross the wood making links with Chartham and New House Lane. There is a car park at the entrance.
